Global Indemnity Limited Key Developments

Global Indemnity Limited Announces Unaudited Consolidated Earnings Results for the First Quarter Ended March 31, 2017
May 8 17
Global Indemnity Limited announced unaudited consolidated earnings results for the first quarter ended March 31, 2017. For the quarter, the company reported net premiums written of $111,506,000 against $116,872,000 a year ago. Net premiums earned were $113,126,000 against $121,636,000 a year ago. Net investment income was $8,644,000 against $9,746,000 a year ago. Total revenues were $123,913,000 against $124,845,000 a year ago. Operating income was $11,764,000 or $0.67 diluted per share against $11,991,000 or $0.69 diluted per share a year ago. Income before income taxes was $9,280,000 against $1,953,000 a year ago. Net income was $12,282,000 or $0.70 diluted per share against $7,125,000 or $0.41 basic and diluted per share a year ago. As of March 31, 2017 book value per share was $46.44, an increase of 2.3% compared to book value per share of $45.42 at December 31, 2016.


Global Indemnity Limited, Annual General Meeting, Jun 14, 2017
Apr 28 17
Global Indemnity Limited, Annual General Meeting, Jun 14, 2017, at 13:00 Atlantic Daylight. Location: Global Indemnity Reinsurance Company, Ltd., Seon Place, 141 Front Street Hamilton United Kingdom Agenda: To elect directors to the Board of Directors of the company; to act on various matters concerning Global Indemnity Reinsurance Company, Ltd. and authorization of Global Indemnity Limited; to ratify the appointment of independent auditors and to authorize Board of Directors acting through its Audit Committee to determine its fees; to approve, in a non-binding advisory vote, the compensation of executive officers; to recommend, in a non-binding advisory vote, the frequency of shareholder votes to approve the compensation of named executive officers as disclosed pursuant to the rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission in the company; and to transact other business.


Global Indemnity Limited Announces 7.875% Subordinated Notes Due 2047
Mar 23 17
On March 23, 2017, Global Indemnity Limited completed its previously announced sale of $120 million aggregate principal amount of its 7.875% Subordinated Notes due 2047 (the Firm Notes) to the several underwriters named in Schedule II (the Underwriters) to the Underwriting Agreement, dated March 16, 2017 (the Underwriting Agreement), by and between the Company and Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC, UBS Securities LLC and RBC Capital Markets, LLC, as managers for the Underwriters. Pursuant to the underwriting agreement, the company granted the Underwriters a 30-day option to purchase up to an additional $18 million aggregate principal amount of its 7.875% Subordinated Notes due 2047, solely to cover over-allotments, if any. The notes bear interest at an annual rate equal to 7.875%, payable quarterly in arrears on January 15, April 15, July 15 and October 15 of each year, commencing July 15, 2017. The Notes mature on April 15, 2047. The Company has the right to redeem the Notes in $25 increments, in whole or in part, on April 15, 2022, or on any interest payment date thereafter, at a redemption price equal to 100% of the principal amount of the Notes plus accrued and unpaid interest to, but not including, the date of redemption. The Firm Notes were issued in minimum denominations of $25 and integral multiples. The notes are the company's subordinated unsecured obligations and rank (i) senior to existing and future capital stock, (ii) senior in right of payment to any existing and future junior subordinated debt, (iii) equally in right of payment with any existing unsecured, subordinated debt that the company has issued or that the company may issue in the future that ranks equally with the Notes, including the company's existing 7.75% subordinated notes due 2045, and (iv) subordinate in right of payment to any of the company's existing and future senior debt. In addition, the Notes are structurally subordinated to all existing and future indebtedness, liabilities and other obligations of the company's subsidiaries, including the company's margin borrowing facilities.


